63
00:03:31,130 --> 00:03:33,311
So how's it been for you, like working on a game

64
00:03:33,331 --> 00:03:35,892
that's sort of been open and in public development

65
00:03:35,912 --> 00:03:36,532
for years now?

66
00:03:38,333 --> 00:03:39,533
It's hard.

67
00:03:39,713 --> 00:03:42,574
I would say it doubles the challenge

68
00:03:43,214 --> 00:03:47,435
because when you're not, you know,

69
00:03:47,475 --> 00:03:49,736
when you're working on a game that is unannounced

70
00:03:49,916 --> 00:03:52,297
or is at least, you know, it's just not in players' hands,

71
00:03:52,317 --> 00:03:54,798
you can just break everything every day, you know,

72
00:03:55,958 --> 00:03:57,898
and or if something's not working,

73
00:03:57,938 --> 00:03:59,739
just completely throw it out, redesign it overnight.

74
00:04:01,881 --> 00:04:17,186
When you're in early access, even though the ostensible point of early access is to bring players into a development process where the game is going to be evolving and changing potentially drastically over time,

75
00:04:17,906 --> 00:04:24,008
the reality is that you're just in a live support mode for a live game, and you kind of have to treat it that way.

76
00:04:24,528 --> 00:04:29,930
And it's still, you know, being on Xbox, it meant that we had to go through.

77
00:04:31,378 --> 00:04:34,819
It was very, very similar to just being a fully released game.

78
00:04:35,699 --> 00:04:39,640
We still had the requirement to go through certain patient stages to get updates out.

79
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:46,661
We had to have all of our ducks in a row in terms of publishing, in terms of store presence.

80
00:04:47,982 --> 00:04:49,902
And then you have a community to manage.

81
00:04:50,162 --> 00:04:54,583
And even though you're in early access, people develop their favorite features.

82
00:04:55,303 --> 00:04:59,724
It becomes very difficult to make certain changes without.

83
00:05:01,878 --> 00:05:03,018
Disappointing certain people.

84
00:05:03,699 --> 00:05:07,621
And so it's, and then the speed with which you can,

85
00:05:07,941 --> 00:05:10,402
the speed at which you can work is definitely slowed down

86
00:05:10,462 --> 00:05:13,503
because each and every update has to, you know,

87
00:05:14,644 --> 00:05:16,365
keep the game going, you know, you can't break the game

88
00:05:17,045 --> 00:05:18,586
to the greatest extent possible.

89
00:05:18,606 --> 00:05:19,826
And we had, throughout early access,

90
00:05:19,846 --> 00:05:21,787
we had kind of a caveat saying like,

91
00:05:22,708 --> 00:05:25,189
each update has the potential to disrupt your save game.

92
00:05:25,729 --> 00:05:26,990
We're not guaranteeing that everything

93
00:05:27,010 --> 00:05:28,631
is always fully backwards compatible.

94
00:05:28,651 --> 00:05:30,412
We had a few updates that were.

95
00:05:31,156 --> 00:05:35,438
that were pretty big changes, like when we completely changed the base building paradigm at one point.

96
00:05:35,478 --> 00:05:41,420
So I, you know, we had to write some code that would actually kind of give you some credit for the old base that you had.

97
00:05:43,341 --> 00:05:47,402
And so it's, and that takes, that's certainly a big toll on development.

98
00:05:47,422 --> 00:05:59,127
I estimate that it took us probably twice as long to make this game that we're playing today as it would have if we were not in early access and we were not trying to sustain the game through.

99
00:05:59,799 --> 00:06:02,821
monthly or every six weeks and have an update.

100
00:06:03,982 --> 00:06:06,464
Was that something you were sort of aware of as you were doing it,

101
00:06:06,484 --> 00:06:08,225
or is that something you've come to realize in hindsight?

102
00:06:09,546 --> 00:06:14,490
A little bit of both. I think we knew that there would be a toll and it would be a lot

103
00:06:14,510 --> 00:06:20,454
of extra work going in, but I don't think we realized quite how much. Yeah.

104
00:06:20,874 --> 00:06:24,717
So what was the value to you as a team when you were working through this process?

105
00:06:24,917 --> 00:06:27,699
Why did you decide to stick with this sort of open development philosophy,

106
00:06:27,719 --> 00:06:28,880
even though it was taking you more time?

107
00:06:32,808 --> 00:06:41,390
The original impetus was really, it was the only option or best option we had to maintain

108
00:06:41,430 --> 00:06:45,411
control over development without bringing in a publisher or something like that.

109
00:06:46,812 --> 00:06:51,613
And we have a really great community, a very supportive community.

110
00:06:51,973 --> 00:06:57,615
And so it's been, from that perspective, it's been very nice to learn how to work with our

111
00:06:57,635 --> 00:06:59,795
community and learn how to take their feedback.

112
00:07:00,757 --> 00:07:05,538
And it's also given us the opportunity to learn.

113
00:07:05,558 --> 00:07:07,618
You know, like it should be said that when I,

114
00:07:07,738 --> 00:07:10,599
when we started, I think when we launched into early access,

115
00:07:11,619 --> 00:07:14,100
it was like System Error was not a company

116
00:07:14,880 --> 00:07:16,380
in the traditional sense of a game company

117
00:07:16,460 --> 00:07:17,440
in the sense that we didn't have,

