00:08:14,270 --> 00:08:17,713
who are echoing the fact that this is a well-loved and well-received game.

137
00:08:19,254 --> 00:08:22,496
How do you feel about your two experiences or those two ways of making games,

138
00:08:22,536 --> 00:08:26,439
which is sort of like closeted and sort of hidden away from the world for years

139
00:08:26,459 --> 00:08:29,281
versus sort of being open and upfront?

140
00:08:29,936 --> 00:08:32,077
Sort of just like by the seat of your pants.

141
00:08:32,777 --> 00:08:36,618
Do you think you want to go back to sort of a more closeted approach?

142
00:08:36,679 --> 00:08:41,280
Or is there just a lot of value in the early access open development philosophy?

143
00:08:43,481 --> 00:08:44,221
I don't know.

144
00:08:44,241 --> 00:08:49,243
We certainly don't want to be as closeted as most AAA developers are.

145
00:08:49,483 --> 00:08:51,564
You know, we were used to working on teams.

146
00:08:52,545 --> 00:08:55,866
So I came from myself and two of the other founders.

147
00:08:56,186 --> 00:08:56,926
We had met each other.

148
00:08:58,232 --> 00:09:01,274
through working on Halo at Microsoft, 3.3 Industries.

149
00:09:02,395 --> 00:09:06,117
Adam, the other co-founder, he worked at Ubisoft,

150
00:09:06,137 --> 00:09:10,920
and we had, and Riley, who's our fifth and our sound designer,

151
00:09:10,980 --> 00:09:13,101
he came from working at EA and Disney.

152
00:09:13,962 --> 00:09:15,123
So we all worked at huge companies

153
00:09:15,163 --> 00:09:16,604
with hundreds of people at these studios,

154
00:09:16,844 --> 00:09:20,306
and at those studios, you, as an individual developer,

155
00:09:20,606 --> 00:09:22,807
have no interaction with the community at all.

156
00:09:24,729 --> 00:09:25,109
Yeah.

157
00:09:25,129 --> 00:09:27,430
And you are told that you are not allowed to say anything.

158
00:09:28,308 --> 00:09:31,871
And there are dire consequences if you go and start talking about the game,

159
00:09:31,931 --> 00:09:34,133
or even once the game is released, just saying the wrong thing.

160
00:09:35,794 --> 00:09:38,156
And so from that perspective, we definitely don't want to go back to that.

161
00:09:38,476 --> 00:09:43,781
And I think the relationship, the kind of interaction that we've developed with our community

162
00:09:43,801 --> 00:09:46,763
is something that we cherish and we want to hold on to that.

163
00:09:48,104 --> 00:09:50,046
As far as whether we'll do early access again,

164
00:09:50,226 --> 00:09:54,169
it's really just a decision about what is going to be...

165
00:09:55,657 --> 00:10:03,381
How are we going to be delivering the best products to that community most efficiently?

166
00:10:03,401 --> 00:10:10,504
I think Early Access has a bad reputation now.

167
00:10:10,544 --> 00:10:15,386
It was developing a bad reputation when we started.

168
00:10:15,406 --> 00:10:20,308
