170
00:10:24,474 --> 00:10:25,715
We're never going to see anything for it.

171
00:10:27,615 --> 00:10:33,237
But yeah, I think it really depends.

172
00:10:33,277 --> 00:10:34,758
I think that if we do early access again,

173
00:10:35,178 --> 00:10:40,580
we'd like to shorten the cycle and try to present a game when

174
00:10:40,640 --> 00:10:43,161
it enters early access that's closer to the finished product.

175
00:10:43,221 --> 00:10:44,902
Because I think Astroneer was so,

176
00:10:45,962 --> 00:10:49,064
it needed so much work when we started that.

177
00:10:49,224 --> 00:10:50,284
And there was so many other games

178
00:10:50,304 --> 00:10:52,585
that had gone through early access that were

179
00:10:52,605 --> 00:10:53,385
more representative of.

180
00:10:54,585 --> 00:10:57,908
People are maybe not used to having to go through

181
00:10:57,928 --> 00:10:59,749
as much iteration as we did.

182
00:11:01,190 --> 00:11:04,292
Yeah, I want to agree with you,

183
00:11:04,312 --> 00:11:07,654
but it feels like the public perception of early access

184
00:11:07,674 --> 00:11:09,835
might be changing and there might be sort of more recognition

185
00:11:09,875 --> 00:11:11,837
that it can be a really valuable and useful pipeline

186
00:11:11,877 --> 00:11:12,937
for the right team.

187
00:11:12,977 --> 00:11:15,119
I think games like Astroneer go a long way

188
00:11:15,159 --> 00:11:16,960
towards proving that.

